<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL / DAILY REPORT; AROUND THE MAJOR LEAGUES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 AROUND THE MAJOR LEAGUES 
</P>
<P>
 The Cleveland Indians on Friday trimmed their roster to one over the opening 
day limit, designating outfielder Ruben Amaro for assignment, optioning 
left-hander Brian Barnes to the minors and adding reliever Steve Farr to the 
25-man roster. 
</P>
<P>
 Amaro, acquired from Philadelphia last November for Heathcliff Slocumb, hit 
.291 in 101 games for the Phillies' Triple-A Scranton- Wilkes- Barre team. In 
25 games in the majors, he hit .333. 
</P>
<P>
 Barnes, who was 2-6 with a 4.41 ERA and three saves in 52 games for Montreal 
last year, was acquired in a December trade that sent Randy Milligan to the 
Expos. Barnes was sent to Triple-A Charlotte. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 San Diego Padre pitcher Doug Brocail is scheduled to undergo arthroscopic 
surgery Monday to remove a bone spur from his right elbow, and is expected to 
miss the first two months of the season. 
</P>
<P>
 Brocail failed to win a spot in the rotation and was scheduled to work out of 
the bullpen. He was 4-13 with a 4.56 ERA in 24 starts for the Padres last year 
after being promoted from Triple-A Las Vegas. 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Facing another money-losing year, Oakland Athletics are seeking stadium lease 
concessions and, failing that, might invoke a clause that could lead to the 
sale and possible move of the club. 
</P>
<P>
 "We have sat down with Coliseum, city and county officials to discuss our 
financial situation and told them: "This can't continue. Not under this 
ownership,' " A's President Sandy Alderson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Team owner Walter Haas Jr. does not want to sell or move the team but cannot 
keep absorbing financial losses, Alderson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Haas reportedly has discussed invoking a lease clause that would give the city 
six months to find a local buyer at a price set by Haas. 
</P>
<P>
 If a purchaser wasn't found within that time frame, Haas "could sell, keep the 
team in Oakland, move it. There are a whole host of options," Alderson said. 
</P>
<P>
 The A's lost $3 million in 1993 and they project up to a $10-million loss in 
1994. The team has turned a profit only three times in the last 13 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
