<HEADLINE>
<P>
OFF THE TICKER: HOLY TOLEDO!; WATCH OUT, HONEY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Couples beware: The next time you are alone and a pretty woman bats her baby 
blues at you or a hunky man flexes his muscles in your direction, it could be 
the love police on patrol. 
</P>
<P>
 Test-A-Mate is a new business here that uses good-looking decoys to test a 
partner's loyalty. 
</P>
<P>
 For $250 and a picture of your mate, the curious can browse through 
Test-A-Mate's photo album of attractive women and men and select the decoy they 
think their companion will go for. 
</P>
<P>
 The customer tells Test-A-Mate where their mate hangs out and the decoy will 
show up and sit near him or her, but won't speak unless spoken to, said Ron 
Allen, general manager of Checkmate Investigations Inc. Test-A-Mate is a 
Checkmate division. 
</P>
<P>
 In a week or two, customers receive a report card on their mates. 
</P>
<P>
 "We're using Toledo as a test market," Allen said. "We're getting all the bugs 
out of the system." 
</P>
<P>
 According to its brochure, "Test-A-Mate is a service that was designed to test 
the honesty, devotion, dedication and loyalty of your mate. ... The purpose of 
this service is to help solidify relationships of people that are married or 
single." 
</P>
</TEXT>
