<HEADLINE>
<P>
ROOKIE PAULSON SHOOTS RECORD 62 TO TAKE LEAD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Dennis Paulson, a 31-year-old tour rookie, set a course record and tied the 
tournament record Friday with a 10-under 62 to take a one-stroke lead in the 
Freeport-McMorRan Golf Classic. 
</P>
<P>
 Paulson, who started the day at two over, capped his round with two eagles on 
the back nine to complete 36 holes at 136. 
</P>
<P>
 "I was only three under at the turn, then I knocked a wedge in on the next 
hole for an eagle. I said to my caddie, 'We're making some good shots here. 
Let's just make one good swing at a time,' " Paulson said. 
</P>
<P>
 Paulson, from Palm Desert, broke the course record of 63 set Thursday by Jose 
Maria Olazabal of Spain. The tournament record of 62 was set by Bob Gilder in 
1979. 
</P>
<P>
 Paulson played in six tournaments since finishing 10th in the 1993 qualifying 
tournament, making three cuts, with a best finish of 12th at Pebble Beach. He 
has earned $31,242. 
</P>
<P>
 "We've got a long way to go," Paulson said. "They don't issue a trophy for 
yesterday or today. There are two more rounds before they do that, and I don't 
think I've ever shot like this and then come back and shot a good round the 
next day. It's tough to keep from thinking." 
</P>
<P>
 Olazabal had that problem Friday, following his 63 with a 74 that featured 
five bogeys. He shared second with Ben Crenshaw. 
</P>
<P>
 "I made a few mistakes. I didn't make my putts and I didn't make the right 
club selection sometimes," Olazabal said. "Thanks to what I did yesterday, I'm 
still on the leader board and I have two more days to go." 
</P>
<P>
 Olazabal three-putted the third hole from 21 feet, two-putted the seventh from 
five feet, missed a three-footer for par at the eighth, two-putted the 14th 
from 18 feet and two-putted the 15th from 15 feet. 
</P>
<P>
 "My putting stroke just let me down today," Olazabal said. 
</P>
<P>
 Crenshaw's 68 included six birdies and two bogeys. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm hitting enough good shots to feel pretty good about next week," Crenshaw 
said of the upcoming Masters. "I played pretty well." 
</P>
</TEXT>
